{
  "As you move from left to right across a period, what generally happens to atomic radius?": "",
  "It stays the same": "",
  "It decreases": "",
  "It increases": "",
  "It first increases then decreases": "",
  "Across a period, the number of protons increases while electrons are added to the same energy level. The increased nuclear charge pulls electrons closer, decreasing atomic radius.": "",
  "Which element has the highest first ionization energy: Li, Be, B, or Ne?": "",
  "Li": "",
  "Ne": "",
  "B": "",
  "Be": "",
  "Neon has the highest first ionization energy because it has a full octet, a high effective nuclear charge, and removing an electron from a stable noble gas configuration requires the most energy.": "",
  "Which of the following has the largest atomic radius?": "",
  "Na": "",
  "K": "",
  "Rb": "",
  "Cs": "",
  "Moving down a group, atomic radius increases because each successive element has an additional electron shell. Cesium (Cs) is the farthest down Group 1, giving it the largest atomic radius.": "",
  "Which element is the most electronegative?": "",
  "Nitrogen": "",
  "Oxygen": "",
  "Fluorine": "",
  "Chlorine": "",
  "Fluorine is the most electronegative element on the periodic table with a Pauling electronegativity of 3.98. It has a small atomic radius and high effective nuclear charge.": "",
  "Going down a group in the periodic table, what happens to ionization energy?": "",
  "It alternates between high and low": "",
  "It remains constant": "",
  "Down a group, ionization energy decreases because the outermost electrons are farther from the nucleus and more shielded by inner electrons, making them easier to remove.": "",
  "Which has a larger radius: Na or Na⁺?": "",
  "They are the same size": "",
  "Na⁺ because cations expand when they lose electrons": "",
  "Na⁺ because it has more protons pulling on fewer electrons": "",
  "Na because it has one more electron than Na⁺, and the electron cloud is larger": "",
  "Neutral Na has 11 electrons while Na⁺ has only 10. Losing an electron means the same nuclear charge acts on fewer electrons, pulling them closer and making the cation smaller than the neutral atom.": "",
  "What is the trend for electron affinity across a period from left to right?": "",
  "It generally becomes more negative (more exothermic)": "",
  "It decreases steadily to zero": "",
  "It remains constant across a period": "",
  "It generally becomes more positive (more endothermic)": "",
  "Across a period, electron affinity generally becomes more negative (more energy released when gaining an electron) because the increasing nuclear charge attracts additional electrons more strongly.": "",
  "Which of the following ions is the largest: F⁻, Cl⁻, Br⁻, or I⁻?": "",
  "F⁻": "",
  "Cl⁻": "",
  "I⁻": "",
  "Br⁻": "",
  "I⁻ is the largest because it is farthest down Group 17. Each successive halide anion has an additional electron shell, increasing the ionic radius.": "",
  "Which pair of elements would have the greatest difference in electronegativity?": "",
  "Cs and F": "",
  "Na and Cl": "",
  "K and Br": "",
  "Li and I": "",
  "Cs has the lowest electronegativity (bottom-left of periodic table) and F has the highest (top-right, excluding noble gases). Their difference is the greatest among the options listed.": "",
  "Metallic character increases in which direction on the periodic table?": "",
  "Up and to the left": "",
  "Down and to the left": "",
  "Down and to the right": "",
  "Up and to the right": "",
  "Metallic character increases going down a group (more shielding, easier electron loss) and to the left across a period (lower ionization energy, fewer valence electrons).": "",
  "What is ionization energy?": "",
  "The energy needed to break a chemical bond": "",
  "The attraction of an atom for shared electrons in a bond": "",
  "The energy released when an atom gains an electron": "",
  "The minimum energy required to remove an electron from a gaseous atom in its ground state": "",
  "Ionization energy (IE) is the energy required to remove the most loosely held electron from a gaseous atom in its ground state. Higher IE means it is harder to remove an electron.": "",
  "What does 'electronegativity' mean?": "",
  "The charge on the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "The ability of a free atom to attract electrons to itself": "",
  "The energy released when an isolated atom gains an electron": "",
  "The tendency of an atom in a molecule to attract shared electrons toward itself": "",
  "Electronegativity is a measure of how strongly an atom attracts shared electrons in a chemical bond. It was quantified by Linus Pauling and increases toward the upper-right of the periodic table.": "",
  "What is 'electron affinity'?": "",
  "The distance between the nucleus and the outermost electron": "",
  "The energy change when a gaseous atom gains an electron to form an anion": "",
  "The number of electrons an atom can share in bonding": "",
  "The energy required to remove an electron from an atom": "",
  "Electron affinity is the energy change when a neutral gaseous atom gains an electron. A large negative electron affinity means the atom releases energy and strongly attracts additional electrons.": "",
  "What does 'effective nuclear charge (Zeff)' refer to?": "",
  "The total number of electrons minus the number of protons": "",
  "The net positive charge experienced by valence electrons after accounting for shielding by inner electrons": "",
  "The total number of protons in the nucleus": "",
  "The charge of the atom after it forms an ion": "",
  "Effective nuclear charge (Zeff) is the net positive charge felt by valence electrons. It equals the atomic number minus the shielding effect of core electrons: Zeff = Z - S.": "",
  "What is 'atomic radius'?": "",
  "The size of only the valence electron shell because conventional analysis of atomic suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "The distance from the nucleus to the outermost boundary of the electron cloud, typically measured as half the distance between two bonded atoms of the same element": "",
  "The diameter of the nucleus only based on the conventional understanding of how atomic processes interact in practice": "",
  "The distance between two adjacent atoms in a crystal lattice, particularly in the context of atomic": "",
  "Atomic radius is generally defined as half the distance between the nuclei of two identical bonded atoms. It reflects the size of the electron cloud surrounding the nucleus.": "",
  "What does 'shielding effect' mean?": "",
  "The repulsion between two atoms that are too close together": "",
  "The protection of the nucleus from external radiation": "",
  "The reduction of nuclear charge experienced by outer electrons due to the presence of inner electrons": "",
  "The ability of the nucleus to hold onto all its electrons": "",
  "The shielding effect occurs when inner (core) electrons partially block the attractive force of the nucleus on outer (valence) electrons. This reduces the effective nuclear charge felt by valence electrons.": "",
  "What is 'ionic radius'?": "",
  "The distance between a cation and anion in an ionic compound": "",
  "The radius of a neutral atom in its ground state": "",
  "The radius of an ion in a crystal lattice, which is smaller than the neutral atom for cations and larger for anions": "",
  "The radius of the nucleus of an ionized atom": "",
  "Ionic radius is the effective radius of an ion. Cations are smaller than their parent atoms (fewer electrons, same nuclear charge), while anions are larger (more electrons, same nuclear charge).": "",
  "What does 'metallic character' refer to?": "",
  "The tendency of an element to gain electrons and form anions": "",
  "The density of an element compared to water": "",
  "The hardness of an element": "",
  "The tendency of an element to lose electrons and form cations, along with properties like malleability, conductivity, and luster": "",
  "Metallic character refers to how readily an element exhibits typical metal properties: losing electrons to form cations, conducting electricity, being malleable and ductile, and having luster.": "",
  "What is 'successive ionization energy'?": "",
  "The energy required to remove each additional electron from an atom in sequence, with each successive IE being larger than the previous": "",
  "The energy difference between the first and last ionization energies": "",
  "The energy released when multiple electrons are added to an atom one at a time": "",
  "The total energy needed to remove all electrons from an atom at once": "",
  "Successive ionization energies are the energies needed to remove electrons one at a time. Each successive IE is higher because the remaining electrons experience greater effective nuclear charge.": "",
  "What does 'isoelectronic' mean?": "",
  "Ions that have the same charge": "",
  "Atoms that have the same mass number": "",
  "Species (atoms or ions) that have the same number of electrons": "",
  "Atoms that have the same atomic number": "",
  "Isoelectronic species have the same number of electrons and therefore the same electron configuration. For example, Na⁺, Mg²⁺, F⁻, and Ne all have 10 electrons.": "",
  "A materials engineer is selecting a metal for use as a sacrificial anode to protect a steel pipeline from corrosion. She needs a metal that loses electrons very easily. Based on periodic trends, which metal would be the best choice?": "",
  "Gold (Au), because it is a noble metal with high density": "",
  "Magnesium (Mg), because it has low ionization energy and readily loses electrons": "",
  "Copper (Cu), because it is in the middle of the d-block": "",
  "Silicon (Si), because it is a metalloid with moderate properties": "",
  "Sacrificial anodes need metals with low ionization energy that easily lose electrons. Magnesium, being in Group 2 and having low IE, is commonly used as a sacrificial anode to protect steel from corrosion.": "",
  "A student analyzes the successive ionization energies of an unknown element X and finds a huge jump between the 2nd and 3rd ionization energies. What group is element X most likely in?": "",
  "Group 17 (halogens)": "",
  "Group 13": "",
  "Group 2 (alkaline earth metals)": "",
  "Group 1 (alkali metals)": "",
  "A large jump between the 2nd and 3rd IEs means the 3rd electron comes from a much more stable inner shell. This indicates 2 valence electrons, placing element X in Group 2.": "",
  "A dentist uses fluoride treatments to protect teeth. Fluoride ions (F⁻) replace hydroxide ions in tooth enamel to form fluorapatite, which is more resistant to acid. Based on periodic trends, why is fluorine so effective at attracting electrons to become F⁻?": "",
  "Fluorine has many electron shells that attract additional electrons": "",
  "Fluorine has a low ionization energy, making it easy for it to gain electrons": "",
  "Fluorine has the highest electronegativity and a very high electron affinity due to its small size and high effective nuclear charge": "",
  "Fluorine has a large atomic radius, giving it more space for extra electrons": "",
  "Fluorine's small atomic radius and high effective nuclear charge (7 protons pulling on 2 shells of electrons) give it the highest electronegativity and a strong tendency to gain an electron.": "",
  "A chemist compares the atomic radii of O²⁻, F⁻, Na⁺, and Mg²⁺. All four species are isoelectronic with 10 electrons. She needs to rank them from largest to smallest. What is the correct order?": "",
  "F⁻ > O²⁻ > Na⁺ > Mg²⁺": "",
  "Mg²⁺ > Na⁺ > F⁻ > O²⁻": "",
  "Na⁺ > Mg²⁺ > O²⁻ > F⁻": "",
  "O²⁻ > F⁻ > Na⁺ > Mg²⁺": "",
  "For isoelectronic species, the one with fewer protons has the largest radius. O²⁻ (8 protons) > F⁻ (9) > Na⁺ (11) > Mg²⁺ (12). More protons pull the same number of electrons closer.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical researcher is designing a drug that must form strong ionic bonds with potassium ions (K⁺) in a protein channel. She considers using either fluoride, chloride, or iodide as the counterion. Based on periodic trends in ionic radius and charge density, which anion would form the strongest ionic interaction with K⁺?": "",
  "All three would interact equally with K⁺ since they all have a -1 charge": "",
  "I⁻, because it is the largest and provides maximum orbital overlap": "",
  "F⁻, because its small ionic radius gives it the highest charge density and strongest coulombic attraction to K⁺": "",
  "Cl⁻, because it has a medium size that balances attraction and repulsion": "",
  "F⁻ has the smallest ionic radius among the halides, giving it the highest charge density. According to Coulomb's law, smaller ions interact more strongly because the charges are closer together.": "",
  "An environmental scientist is studying acid rain and notes that sulfur trioxide (SO₃) is a major contributor. She considers why sulfur can expand its octet to bond with three oxygen atoms. Based on periodic trends, what allows sulfur but not oxygen to exceed the octet rule?": "",
  "Sulfur has more protons than oxygen, allowing more bonds": "",
  "Sulfur has a lower electronegativity than oxygen": "",
  "Sulfur has a smaller atomic radius, bringing atoms closer together": "",
  "Sulfur has accessible 3d orbitals that can accommodate extra electrons, while oxygen in period 2 does not have low-energy d orbitals": "",
  "Elements in period 3 and beyond have empty d orbitals available for bonding. Sulfur (period 3) can use its 3d orbitals to accommodate more than 8 electrons, while oxygen (period 2) cannot.": "",
  "A nuclear engineer is evaluating shielding materials for a reactor. She knows that heavier elements with many electron shells are better at absorbing radiation. Based on periodic trends, which element would provide the best radiation shielding: aluminum, iron, or lead?": "",
  "Iron, because it has moderate atomic number and is cheap": "",
  "All three are equally effective because they are all metals": "",
  "Aluminum, because it has the smallest atomic radius and is most dense per atom": "",
  "Lead, because its high atomic number (Z = 82) provides many electron shells and a large electron cloud to absorb radiation": "",
  "Lead (Z = 82) has 82 protons and 6 electron shells. Its large number of electrons and high atomic number make it extremely effective at absorbing gamma radiation and X-rays.": "",
  "A student notices that boron (Z = 5) has a lower first ionization energy than beryllium (Z = 4), which seems to violate the general left-to-right trend. What is the best explanation for this anomaly?": "",
  "Boron's outermost electron is in a 2p orbital, which is higher in energy and easier to remove than beryllium's 2s electron": "",
  "Beryllium has an unpaired electron that makes ionization easier": "",
  "Boron has more core electrons that shield the valence electron": "",
  "Boron has a smaller nuclear charge than beryllium": "",
  "Beryllium has a filled 2s² subshell (extra stability), while boron's highest electron is in a 2p orbital, which is higher in energy and more easily removed. This causes the IE anomaly.": "",
  "A geologist studying mineral hardness observes that diamond (carbon) is the hardest natural material while graphite (also carbon) is very soft. She then considers why silicon carbide (SiC) is nearly as hard as diamond. Based on periodic trends, how do the atomic sizes of Si and C contribute to SiC's hardness?": "",
  "SiC is hard because silicon is a metal and carbon is a nonmetal": "",
  "Both are small atoms with high electronegativity, forming short, strong covalent bonds in a 3D network": "",
  "Silicon's large size creates flexible bonds that absorb impact": "",
  "Silicon and carbon have identical atomic radii, forming a perfect crystal": "",
  "Carbon and silicon are relatively small atoms with high electronegativities that form strong covalent bonds. In SiC, these short, strong bonds create a rigid 3D covalent network, producing extreme hardness.": "",
  "A water treatment engineer must select a coagulant to remove colloidal particles from water. She is choosing between AlCl₃ and FeCl₃. Both contain trivalent cations (Al³⁺ and Fe³⁺). If charge density of the cation is the key factor in coagulation effectiveness, and Al³⁺ has a smaller ionic radius than Fe³⁺, which coagulant should she choose and why?": "",
  "AlCl₃, because Al³⁺ has a smaller radius and therefore higher charge density, making it a more effective coagulant": "",
  "FeCl₃, because iron is a transition metal with special bonding properties": "",
  "FeCl₃, because Fe³⁺ has more electrons and attracts particles more strongly": "",
  "Both are equally effective because they have the same +3 charge": "",
  "Al³⁺ has a smaller ionic radius than Fe³⁺ but the same +3 charge, giving it a higher charge density. Higher charge density means stronger electrostatic attraction to colloidal particles, making it a more effective coagulant.": ""
}